I"Z<p>The Chingford Hall estate has been earmarked for renewal, according to the borough’s <a href="https://walthamforest.gov.uk/sites/default/files/Final%20Draft%20Local%20Plan_July2019_Web%20optimised_Part1.pdf">draft Local Plan</a>.</p>

<p><img src="/images/chrenewal.png" class="img-fluid rounded img-thumbnail" /></p>

<p><img src="/images/chrenewal2.png" class="img-fluid rounded img-thumbnail" /></p>

<p>The estate dates from the early 90s when it replaced the now-demolished <a href="http://www.towerblock.eca.ed.ac.uk/development/chingford-hall-stage-ii">60s Chingford Hall estate</a> as one of the government’s <a href="https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/home-news/this-is-a-council-estate-the-government-spent-pounds-150000-on-each-house-why-1322746.html">Housing Action Trust</a> regeneration schemes. The Waltham Forest Housing Action Trust closed down in 2002 and the homes were <a href="https://www.peabody.org.uk/neighbourhoods/waltham-forest/chingford/about">transferred</a> to housing association Peabody.</p>

